Literature de Courdelle is a tradition full of authentic expressions, irony, complex poetry, no matter how simple it may seem. The date was not chosen by chance: it coincides with the birthday of the poet Leandro Gomez de Barros in 1865[15]. In September 2018 The National Institute of Historical and Artistic Heritage recognized Literature de Courdel as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Brazil[16]. The Tsavo Man-Eaters were two man-eating lions operating in the area of ​​the Tsavo River (modern Kenya) in 1898, during the construction of the Uganda Railway. In March In 1898, construction began on a permanent bridge across the Tsavo River - a section of the Uganda Railway.